1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,279
The Gettysburg National Military Park is in the small town of Gettysburg in the eastern state of Pennsylvania.

2
00:00:09,279 --> 00:00:19,416
Much of the area around Gettysburg still looks like it did in the 1860s, during the American Civil War.

3
00:00:19,416 --> 00:00:23,654
The town is in the middle of good farmland.

4
00:00:23,654 --> 00:00:33,595
Roads pass through Gettysburg that lead to Baltimore, Washington, D.C., and other eastern cities.

5
00:00:33,595 --> 00:00:38,483
It is hard to believe that two huge armies fought there.

6
00:00:38,483 --> 00:00:47,952
One fighting force was the United States Army of the Potomac, commanded by General George Meade.

7
00:00:47,952 --> 00:00:56,098
The other was the Confederate Army of Northern Virginia led by General Robert E. Lee.

8
00:00:56,098 --> 00:01:02,759
Lee’s troops had moved north into Pennsylvania from Virginia.

9
00:01:02,759 --> 00:01:18,675
Lee believed that a Southern win of a battle on Northern land would force a negotiated settlement of the Civil War and mean independence for the Confederate States.

10
00:01:18,675 --> 00:01:25,074
The battle of Gettysburg began on July 1, 1863.

11
00:01:25,074 --> 00:01:31,312
About 170,000 soldiers fought for three days.

12
00:01:31,312 --> 00:01:40,486
When it ended on July 3, more than 50,000 soldiers were dead, wounded or missing.

13
00:01:40,486 --> 00:01:43,986
Lee’s army lost the battle.

14
00:01:43,986 --> 00:01:52,523
Many visitors start their visit to Gettysburg at the Gettysburg Museum of the Civil War.

15
00:01:52,523 --> 00:01:58,813
The museum has a large collection of Civil War objects.

16
00:01:58,813 --> 00:02:10,109
The museum has more than 1 million artifacts, from soldiers’ private notebooks and clothing to maps of the battlefield.

17
00:02:10,109 --> 00:02:16,046
The museum also houses the Gettysburg cyclorama painting.

18
00:02:16,046 --> 00:02:21,967
This kind of artwork completely surrounds the people looking at it.

19
00:02:21,967 --> 00:02:33,644
The painting shows the artist’s vision of the final major attack of the battle on July 3, 1863.

20
00:02:33,644 --> 00:02:39,367
Over time, it has come to be called Pickett's Charge.

21
00:02:39,367 --> 00:02:46,740
George Pickett was one of several Confederate commanders ordered to make the charge.

22
00:02:46,740 --> 00:02:54,883
The Confederate soldiers reached a point close to the northern lines and headquarters.

23
00:02:54,883 --> 00:03:00,095
Today, the point is called the “High Water Mark.”

24
00:03:00,095 --> 00:03:05,533
Northern forces then turned the Confederates back.

25
00:03:05,533 --> 00:03:13,078
The charge failed. Southern forces would never again reach so far north.

26
00:03:13,078 --> 00:03:21,834
Soon after the battle, people began to visit Gettysburg to try to understand what happened there.

27
00:03:21,834 --> 00:03:31,239
One of those visitors, on November 19, 1863, was President Abraham Lincoln.

28
00:03:31,239 --> 00:03:39,186
He was invited to help dedicate a burial ground for Union soldiers killed in the battle.

29
00:03:39,186 --> 00:03:43,149
Lincoln spoke for just two minutes.

30
00:03:43,149 --> 00:03:53,399
But his speech, known as “The Gettysburg Address,” is one of the most famous pieces of American oratory.

31
00:03:53,399 --> 00:03:58,681
I'm Mario Ritter, Jr.